>just feels like common sense
eh, I feel like they may seem like common sense to most people, but when people actually get down to writing they start to get hanged up on certain things to the point of driving them mad. Sometimes it's good for them to take a step back and took at it holistically, and remind themselves that their are other parts of the story that they can focus on.

you can do one thing "wrong" in your story, but make it up by doing other things really "right" to the point that the other "wrong" stuff becomes irrelevant.

For instance in "Hair of the Dog", anon and volfa fall in love in less than 6-12 hours! And their relationship afterwards feels like they been together for months. Any real scrutiny of that story, would show the timeline as being absurd! But the story works because the dialogue and characterization drive the story that almost in a way "distracts" from that.

I feel like these are both slightly awkward ways to phrase things. The most natural way would be:
"Anon has a waifur, who he loves. He wants to marry her, and because of this, he tries to romance her."
Or
"Anon has a waifur and he loves her. Because of this, he wants to marry her, so he tries to romance her."
This is how I do it. It's direct, simple, easy to follow.
Also, I wouldn't say any of that is "story structure" per se, that's more background information. Story structure would be describing the actual events that are happening in the sequence they happen. Anon loving the waifur probably didn't start right before he tried to romance her.
